# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: tmux
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This document gives a brief description of some of tmux's more advanced features and some examples.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] However, many of the features discussed are useful both interactively and when scripting.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux creates a directory for the user in `/tmp` and the server then creates a socket in that directory.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Sometimes it is convenient to create separate tmux servers, perhaps to ensure an important process is completely isolated or to test a tmux configuration.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This can be done by using the `-L` flag which creates a socket in `/tmp` but with a name other than `default`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The socket used by a running server can be seen with the `socket_path` format.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] An alert in a pane does two things for each session containing the pane's window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Firstly, it sets a flag on the window in the window list, but only if the window is not the current window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Alert flags on a window are cleared as soon as the window becomes the current window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `C-b M-n` and `C-b M-p` key bindings move to the next or previous window with an alert, using the `-a` flag to the `next-window` and `previous-window` commands.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Secondly, it may show a message in the status line, sound a bell in the outside terminal, or both.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Whether this is a bell or a message is controlled by the `visual-bell`, `visual-activity` and `visual-silence` options.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Each tmux session has default working directory.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is the working directory used for each new pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When a window or pane is created, a working directory may be given with `-c` to `new-window` or `split-window`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux can try to read the current working directory of a pane from outside the pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is available in the `pane_current_path` format.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Respawning a pane or window is a way to start a different (or restart the same) program without need to recreate the window, maintaining its size, position and index.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `respawn-pane` command respawns a pane and `respawn-window` a window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If a program is still running in the pane or window, the commands will refuse to work.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Like `split-window`, `respawn-pane` and `respawn-window` have a `-c` flag to set the working directory.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `respawn-pane` and `respawn-window` are useful with the `remain-on-exit` option.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When this is on, panes are not automatically killed when the program running in them exits.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Instead, a message is shown and the pane remains as it was.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is called a dead pane, and `respawn-pane` or `respawn-window` can be used to start the same or a different program.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Every window has a size, its horizontal and vertical dimensions.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A window's size is determined from the size of the clients attached to sessions it is linked to.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A window's size is not changed when it not linked to sessions that are attached.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If a window has never been linked to an attached session - for example when created as part of `new-session` with `-d` - it gets its size from the `default-size` option.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When a window is larger than the client showing it, the visible area tracks the cursor position.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] These keys may be used to view different areas of the window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The visible area is a property of the client, so detaching the client or changing the current window will reset to the cursor position.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] These keys are bound to the `refresh-client` command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A window size for an existing window may be set using the `resize-window` commmand.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This sets the size and automatically sets the `window-size` option to `manual` for that window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows any new changes to a pane to be piped to a command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This may be used to, for example, make a log of a pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `-I` flag to `pipe-pane` sends the output of a command to a pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Used like this, `pipe-pane` with `-I` is similar to the `send-keys` command covered in a later section.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `-o` flag will toggle piping - starting if it is not already started, otherwise stopping it.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A pane's title can be set by the program running in the pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the program was running outside tmux it would set the outside terminal title - normally shown in the *X(7)* window title.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Because tmux can have multiple programs running inside it, there is a pane title for each rather than only one.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The pane title is different from the window name which is used only by tmux and is the same for all panes in a window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux shows the pane title for the active pane in quotes on the right of the status line.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] However there is nothing to stop the program inside tmux changing the title again after this.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The default title includes the names of the attached session and current window as well as the pane title for the active pane and the indexes of any windows with alerts.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This can be changed with the `set-titles-string` option.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux handles most mouse behaviour by mapping mouse events to key bindings.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Mouse keys have special names which are the event, followed by the button number if any, then the area where the mouse event took place.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Terminals only support three buttons and the mouse wheel.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Commands bound to a mouse key binding can use `-t` with the mouse target (`=` or `{mouse}`) to tell tmux they want to use the pane or window where the mouse event took place.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When the program running in a pane can itself handle the mouse, `send-keys` can be used with the `-M` flag to pass the mouse event through to that program.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `mouse_any_flag` format variable is true if the program has turned the mouse on.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Almost all commands work the same way when run using the `tmux` binary as when run from a key binding or the command prompt inside tmux.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux is normally scripted using shell script but of course other languages can be used.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] All examples in this document are intended for a shell based on the Bourne shell.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Formats are an important part of scripting tmux and it is useful to be familiar with them, see this document and the manual page section.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Scripts can vary widely in intended use and that can affect how they are written.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A script that is only run interactively from a key binding may be able to assume the current window or active pane won't change while the script is running, so have no need to worry about targets.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A script designed to set up a new session, or run from another program, may have to be more careful.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Every pane, window and session in tmux has a unique identifier (ID) set by the server.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Different tmux servers can use the same IDs but within a running server each is never changed or reused.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] IDs allow scripts to target a pane, window or session and be guaranteed they are always the same even if they are killed, moved or renamed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When many tmux commands are run, they have to work out which session, window or pane they should affect.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is known as the target and is made up of a session, a window and a pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Not all of these components are used by every command, for example `split-window` needs to know which window to target, but doesn't care about the session or pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The target can be specified to most commands using the `-t` flag - this is described in the next section.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If `-t` is not given, the default target is used.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] How tmux works out the default target depends on where the command is run from.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Commands run from a program running inside tmux, for example typed at a shell prompt in a pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] In this case, tmux doesn't know which client the command was typed into, because it could have been run from a script, or delayed by *sleep(1)*, or several other things.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] However, tmux may know the name of the *tty(4)* or *pty(4)* where the command was run.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If it does, it can use that to work out the pane, because each *tty(4)* or *pty(4)* belongs to exactly one pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Even if the *tty(4)* or *pty(4)* isn't available, the pane ID may be in the `TMUX_PANE` environment variable.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If tmux can find the pane, then it has the window as well, because each pane belongs to one window.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If that window belongs to only one session, that gives the session and window for the default target (tmux will always use the active pane in the window it finds).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the window belongs to multiple sessions, then tmux picks the most recently used session.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the window is linked into the session multiple times (so it has multiple window indexes), then the current window is used if the window is the current window in the session, otherwise the lowest window index is used.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Commands run from a program running outside tmux, like a shell prompt in a different *xterm(1)* that isn't running tmux.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] For this case, tmux has no information about the target from the environment at all.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] So it picks the most recently used session and uses its current window and active pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Most commands accept a `-t` argument to give the target session, window or pane instead of relying on the default target.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Commands typically want either a session, a window or a pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The usage of a command shows which; they can be seen with `list-commands` or in the manual page.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A target is made up of three parts: the session, window and pane.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Any of these three components may be omitted, in which case if it is needed tmux will work out what is most appropriate, similarly to how it works out the default target.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If neither `:` nor `.` appears in the target, tmux interprets it differently depending what the command needs.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the command wants `target-pane` then `-t1` would be tried first as a pane and only as a window if there is no pane 1 found; if the command wants `target-window` then `-t1` will only look for the window at index 1.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This behaviour is effective when tmux is used interactively but for scripting care must be taken that targets are correct.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is best done by noting whether a command wants a session, a window or a pane and by using IDs and the full target the command needs.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] In a target, each of `session`, `window` and `pane` can have several different forms.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The exact name of a session prefixed with an `=`, for example `=mysession`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This will only match the session named `mysession`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] For example, `my` will match `mysession` or `myothersession`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A pattern to match against the session name.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This can have `*` and `?` wildcards: `f*` will match `foo` but not `bar`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A window index, for example `1` for window 1, `99` for window `99`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `{start}` (or `^`) for the lowest window index or `{end}` (or `$`) for the highest.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `{last}` (or `!`) for the last window, `{next}` (or `+`) for the next and `{previous}` (or `-`) for the previous.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `split-window`, `new-window` and `new-session` commands all have a `-P` flag which prints the target of the new pane, window or session to `stdout`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This allows scripts to reliably target it with subsequent commands.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] There are three main ways to get information from the tmux server: list commands, `display-message` and `show-options`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The list commands are `list-panes`, `list-windows` and `list-sessions`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `list-sessions` lists all sessions in the server.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Each of these commands has a `-F` flag which gives the format each line of output.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `display-message` command is used to print individual formats.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Options are shown using the `show-options` command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `send-keys` command can be used to send key presses to a pane as if they had been pressed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] It takes multiple arguments. tmux checks if each argument is the name of a key and if so the appropriate escape sequence is sent for that key; if the argument does not match a key, it is sent as it is.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Sends the five characters in `hello`, followed by an Enter key press (a newline character).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Sends the escape sequences for the `F1` and `C-F2` keys.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Existing pane content can be captured with the `capture-pane` command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This can save its output to a paste buffer or, more usefully, write it to `stdout` by giving the `-p` flag.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `-S` and `-E` flags give the starting and ending line numbers.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Zero is the first visible line and negative lines go into the history.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The special value `-` means the start of the history or the end of the visible content.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows panes to be created without a running command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] When tmux reads a configuration file, it is processed in two broad steps: parsing and execution.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The command is parsed and split into a set of arguments.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] For example take the command: `new -A -sfoo top` It is first split up into a list of four: `new`, `-A`, `-sfoo` and `top`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This list is processed again and tmux looks up the command, so it knows it is `new-session` with arguments `-A`, `-s foo` and `top`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The command is placed at the end of a command queue.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Once all of the configuration file is parsed, execution takes place: the commands are executed from the command queue in order.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A similar process takes place for commands read from the command prompt or as an argument to another command (such as `if-shell`).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] These are pretty much the same as a configuration file with only one line.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] For commands run from the shell, steps 1 and 2 are skipped - configuration file directives are not supported, and the shell splits the command into arguments before giving it to tmux.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This split into parsing and execution does not often have any visible effect but occasionally it matters.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This will not work as expected, because the `set-environment` command takes place during execution and the expansion of `FOO` takes place during parsing.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Because both `FOO=bar` and expansion of `FOO` happen during parsing.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Although the `set-environment` happens during execution, `FOO` is not used until `display-message` is executed and expands its argument as a format.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Care must be taken with commands that take another command as an argument, because there may be multiple parsing stages.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux supports some special syntax in the configuration file to allow more flexible configuration.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is all processed when the configuration file is parsed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Conditional directives allow parts of the configuration file to be processed only if a condition is true.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the given format is true (is not empty and not 0 after being expanded), then commands are executed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Because these directives are processed when the configuration file is parsed, they can't use the results of commands - the commands (whether outside the conditional or in the true or false branch) are not executed until later when the configuration file has been completely parsed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If there is any output, the active pane is switched into view mode.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `run-shell` blocks execution of subsequent commands until the command is finished.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `-b` flag disables this and runs the command in the background.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `if-shell` is a versatile command that allows a choice between two tmux commands to be made based on a shell command or (with `-F`) a format.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The first argument is a condition, the second the command to run when it is true and the third the command to run when it is false.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If `-F` is given, the first condition argument is a format.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A format is true if it expands to a string that is not empty and not 0.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Without `-F`, the first argument is a shell command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Note that `if-shell` is different from the `%if` directive.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `%if` is interpreted when a configuration file is parsed; `if-shell` is a command that is run with other commands and can be used in key bindings.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows sections of a configuration file to be quoted using `{` and `}`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is designed to allow complex commands and command sequences to be expressed more clearly, particularly where a command takes another command as an argument.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Text between `{` and `}` is treated as a string without any modification.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Some tmux options may be set to multiple values, these are called array options.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Each value has an index which is shown in `[` and `]` after the option name.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Array indexes can have gaps, so an array with just index 0 and 999 is fine.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The array options are `command-alias`, `terminal-features`, `terminal-overrides`, `status-format`, `update-environment` and `user-keys`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] `-a` can accept multiple values separated by commas.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows custom commands by defining command aliases.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Note this is different from the short alias of each command (such as `lsw` for `list-windows`).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Command aliases are defined with the `command-alias` server option.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is an array option where each entry has a number.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Taking `command-alias[4]` as an example, this means that the `choose-window` command is expanded to `choose-tree -w`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A custom command alias is added by adding a new index to the array.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Any subsequent flags or arguments given to the entered command are appended to the replaced command.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows custom options to be set, these are called user options and can be pane, window, session or server options.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] All user options are strings and the names must be prefixed by `@`.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] There are no other restrictions on the value.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] User options can be used to store a custom value from a script or key binding.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Because tmux doesn't already know about the option name, the `-w` flag must be given for window options, or `-s` for server.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] User options are useful for scripting, see this section as well.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux allows a set of custom key definitions.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is useful on the rare occasion where terminals send (or can be configured to send) unusual keys sequences that are not recognised by tmux by default.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] User keys are added with the `user-keys` server option.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This is an array option where each item is a sequence that tmux matches to a `UserN` key.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] A custom key table is one with a name other than the four default (`root`, `prefix`, `copy-mode` and `copy-mode-vi`).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] Each client has a current key table, which may be set to no key table.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If it doesn't match, the key is looked up in the client's key table.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the client has no key table, it is first switched into the key table given by the `key-table` option (or the `copy-mode` or `copy-mode-vi` key table if in copy mode).
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If a key binding is found in the table, its command is executed.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If no key binding is found, tmux looks for an `Any` key binding and if one is found executes its command instead.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If the key does not repeat, the client is reset to no key table and waits for the next key press.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] If it does repeat, the client is left with the key table where the key was found so the next key press will also try that table first.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] The `switch-client` command's `-T` flag can be used to explicitly set the client's key table, so when the next key is pressed, it is looked up in that key table.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] This can be used to bind chains of commands or to have multiple prefixes with different commands.
[src:tmux/advanced-use] tmux can update the system clipboard when text is copied, for information see this document.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux is a program which runs in a terminal and allows multiple other terminal programs to be run inside it.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each program inside tmux gets its own terminal managed by tmux, which can be accessed from the single terminal where tmux is running - this is called multiplexing and tmux is a terminal multiplexer.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux - and any programs running inside it - may be detached from the terminal where it is running (the outside terminal) and later reattached to the same or another terminal.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Programs run inside tmux may be full screen interactive programs like *vi(1)* or *top(1)*, shells like *bash(1)* or *ksh(1)*, or any other program that can be run in a Unix terminal.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] There is a powerful feature set to access, manage and organize programs inside tmux, both interactively and from scripts.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This document gives an overview of some of tmux's key concepts, a description of how to use the main features interactively and some information on basic customization and configuration.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Note that this document may mention features only available in the latest tmux release.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Only the latest tmux release is supported.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Releases are made approximately every six months.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux may be installed from package management systems on most major platforms.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] See this document for instructions on how to install tmux or how to build it from source.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux has a set of basic concepts and terms it is important to be familiar with.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This section gives a description of how the terminals inside tmux are grouped together and the various terms tmux uses.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux keeps all its state in a single main process, called the tmux server.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This runs in the background and manages all the programs running inside tmux and keeps track of their output.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The tmux server is started automatically when the user runs a tmux command and by default exits when there are no running programs.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Users attach to the tmux server by starting a client.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This takes over the terminal where it is run and talks to the server using a socket file in `/tmp`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each client runs in one terminal, which may be an *X(7)* terminal such as *xterm(1)*, the system console, or a terminal inside another program (such as tmux itself).
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each client is identified by the name of the outside terminal where it is started, for example `/dev/ttypf`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Every terminal inside tmux belongs to one pane, this is a rectangular area which shows the content of the terminal inside tmux.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Because each terminal inside tmux is shown in only one pane, the term pane can be used to mean all of the pane, the terminal and the program running inside it.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The screenshot to the right shows tmux with panes.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A window is made up of one or more panes which together cover its entire area - so multiple panes may be visible at the same time.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A window normally takes up the whole of the terminal where tmux is attached, but it can be bigger or smaller.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The sizes and positions of all the panes in a window is called the window layout.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Every window has a name - by default tmux will choose one but it can be changed by the user.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Window names do not have to be unique, windows are usually identified by the session and the window index rather than their name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each pane is separated from the panes around it by a line, this is called the pane border.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] There is one pane in each window called the active pane, this is where any text typed is sent and is the default pane used for commands that target the window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The pane border of the active pane is marked in green, or if there are only two panes then the top, bottom, left or right half of the border is green.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Multiple windows are grouped together into sessions.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If a window is part of a session, it is said to be linked to that session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Windows may be linked to multiple sessions at the same time, although mostly they are only in one.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each window in a session has a number, called the window index - the same window may be linked at different indexes in different sessions.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A session's window list is all the windows linked to that session in order of their indexes.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each session has one current window, this is the window displayed when the session is attached and is the default window for any commands that target the session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If the current window is changed, the previous current window becomes known as the last window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A session may be attached to one or more clients, which means it is shown on the outside terminal where that client is running.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Any text typed into that outside terminal is sent to the active pane in the current window of the attached session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Sessions do not have an index but they do have a name, which must be unique.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] To create the first tmux session, tmux is run from the shell.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Without arguments, `new-session` creates a new session and attaches it.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Because this is the first session, the tmux server is started and the tmux run from the shell becomes the first client and attaches to it.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The new session will have one window (at index 0) with a single pane containing a shell.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The shell prompt should appear at the top of the terminal and the green status line at the bottom (more on the status line is below).
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] By default, the first session will be called `0`, the second `1` and so on.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This creates a new session called `mysession`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A command may be given instead of running a shell by passing additional arguments.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If one argument is given, tmux will pass it to the shell, if more than one it runs the command directly.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] By default, tmux calls the first window in the session after whatever is running in it.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `new-session` has other flags - some are covered below.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] When a tmux client is attached, it shows a status line on the bottom line of the screen.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] As new windows are opened, the window list grows - if there are too many windows to fit on the width of the terminal, a `<` or `>` will be added at the left or right or both to show there are hidden windows.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] In the window list, the current window is marked with a `*` after the name, and the last window with a `-`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Once a tmux client is attached, any keys entered are forwarded to the program running in the active pane of the current window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] For keys that control tmux itself, a special key must be pressed first - this is called the prefix key.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The default prefix key is `C-b`, which means the `Ctrl` key and `b`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] In tmux, modifier keys are shown by prefixing a key with `C-` for the control key, `M-` for the meta key (normally `Alt` on modern computers) and `S-` for the shift key.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] These may be combined together, so `C-M-x` means pressing the control key, meta key and `x` together.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] When the prefix key is pressed, tmux waits for another key press and that determines what tmux command is executed.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Keys like this are shown here with a space between them: `C-b c` means first the prefix key `C-b` is pressed, then it is released and then the `c` key is pressed.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Care must be taken to release the `Ctrl` key after pressing `C-b` if necessary - `C-b c` is different from `C-b C-c`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pressing `C-b` twice sends the `C-b` key to the program running in the active pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Every default tmux key binding has a short description to help remember what the key does.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A list of all the keys and their corresponding description texts can be seen by pressing `C-b ?`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A pane in view mode has its own key bindings which do not need the prefix key.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The most important are `Up`, `Down`, `C-Up`, `C-Down` to scroll up and down, and `q` to exit the mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The line number of the top visible line together with the total number of lines is shown in the top right.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `C-b /` shows the description of a single key - a prompt at the bottom of the terminal appears.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pressing a key will show its description in the same place.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] These all have a name like `new-window` or `new-session` or `list-keys` and many also have a shorter alias like `neww` or `new` or `lsk`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Any time a key binding is used, it runs one or more tmux commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] For example, `C-b c` runs the `new-window` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Commands can also be used from the shell, as with `new-session` and `list-keys` above.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each command has zero or more flags, in the same way as standard Unix commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Flags may or may not take a single argument themselves.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] In addition, commands may take additional arguments after the flags.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] All commands and their flags are documented in the tmux manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This document focuses on the available key bindings, but commands are mentioned for information or where there is a useful flag.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] They can be entered from the shell or from the command prompt, described in the next section.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This can be opened by pressing `C-b :` and appears instead of the status line, as shown in this screenshot.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] At the prompt, commands can be entered similarly to how they are at the shell.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Output will either be shown for a short period in the status line, or switch the active pane into view mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] By default, the command prompt uses keys similar to *emacs(1)*; however, if the `VISUAL` or `EDITOR` environment variables are set to something containing `vi` (such as `vi` or `vim` or `nvi`), then *vi(1)*-style keys are used instead.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Multiple commands may be entered together at the command prompt by separating them with a semicolon (`;`).
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Detaching from tmux means that the client exits and detaches from the outside terminal, returning to the shell and leaving the tmux session and any programs inside it running in the background.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] To detach tmux, the `C-b d` key binding is used.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `attach-session` command attaches to an existing session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] By default, attaching to a session does not detach any other clients attached to the same session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `new-session` command has a `-A` flag to attach to an existing session if it exists, or create a new one if it does not.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `-D` flag may be added to make `new-session` also behave like `attach-session` with `-d` and detach any other clients attached to the session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `list-sessions` command (alias `ls`) shows a list of available sessions that can be attached.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If there are no sessions, windows or panes inside tmux, the server will exit.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] It can also be entirely killed using the `kill-server` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A new window can be created in an attached session with the `C-b c` key binding which runs the `new-window` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The new window is created at the first available index - so the second window will have index 1.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The new window becomes the current window of the session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If there are any gaps in the window list, they are filled by new windows.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] So if there are windows with indexes 0 and 2, the next new window will be created as index 1.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A command to be run in the new window may be given to `new-window` in the same way as `new-session`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A pane is created by splitting a window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each time a pane is split into two, each of those panes may be split again using the same key bindings, until the pane becomes too small.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A command to be run in the new pane may be given to `split-window` in the same way as `new-session` and `new-window`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] These are all variations of the `select-window` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] These use the `select-pane` and `display-panes` commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pane numbers are not fixed, instead panes are numbered by their position in the window, so if the pane with number 0 is swapped with the pane with number 1, the numbers are swapped as well as the panes themselves.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux includes a mode where sessions, windows or panes can be chosen from a tree, this is called tree mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] It can be used to browse sessions, windows and panes; to change the attached session, the current window or active pane; to kill sessions, windows and panes; or apply a command to several at once by tagging them.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] There are two key bindings to enter tree mode: `C-b s` starts showing only sessions and with the attached session selected; `C-b w` starts with sessions expanded so windows are shown and with the current window in the attached session selected.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Tree mode splits the window into two sections: the top half has a tree of sessions, windows and panes and the bottom half has a preview of the area around the cursor in each pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] For sessions the preview shows the active panes in as many windows will fit; for windows as many panes as will fit; and for panes only the selected pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Keys to control tree mode do not require the prefix.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The list may be navigated with the `Up` and `Down` keys.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `Enter` changes to the selected item (it becomes the attached session, current window or active pane) and exits the mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `Right` expands the item if possible - sessions expand to show their windows and windows to show their panes.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `Left` collapses the item to hide any windows or panes.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `O` changes the order of the items and `q` exits tree mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Items in the tree are tagged by pressing `t` and untagged by pressing `t` again.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Tagged items are shown in bold and with `*` after their name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] All tagged items may be untagged by pressing `T`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Tagged items may be killed together by pressing `X`, or a command applied to them all by pressing `:` for a prompt.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each item in the tree has as shortcut key in brackets at the start of the line.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pressing this key will immediately choose that item (as if it had been selected and `Enter` pressed).
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The first ten items are keys `0` to `9` and after that keys `M-a` to `M-z` are used.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Tree mode is activated with the `choose-tree` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] A list of clients is available by pressing `C-b D` (that is, `C-b S-d`).
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] This is similar to tree mode and is called client mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Each client is shown in the list in the top half with its name, attached session, size and the time and date when it was last used; the bottom half has a preview of the selected client with as much of its status line as will fit.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The movement and tag keys are the same as tree mode, but others are different, for example the `Enter` key detaches the selected client.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Other than using client mode, the `detach-client` command has a `-a` flag to detach all clients other than the attached client.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pressing `C-b &` prompts for confirmation then kills (closes) the current window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] All panes in the window are killed at the same time.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] These are bound to the `kill-window` and `kill-pane` commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `kill-session` command kills the attached session and all its windows and detaches the client.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] There is no key binding for `kill-session` but it can be used from the command prompt or the `:` prompt in tree mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `C-b $` will prompt for a new name for the attached session.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Likewise, `C-b ,` prompts for a new name for the current window, using the `rename-window` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] tmux allows panes and windows to be swapped with the `swap-pane` and `swap-window` commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] To make swapping easy, a single pane can be marked.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] There is one marked pane across all sessions.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The `C-b m` key binding toggles whether the active pane in the current window in the attached session is the marked pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] `C-b M` clears the marked pane entirely so that no pane is marked.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] The marked pane is shown by a green background to its border and the window containing the marked pane has an `M` flag in the status line.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Once a pane is marked, it can be swapped with the active pane in the current window with the `swap-pane` command, or the window containing the marked pane can be swapped with the current window using the `swap-window` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Panes can additionally be swapped with the pane above or below using the `C-b {` and `C-b }` key bindings.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Moving windows uses the `move-window` command or the `C-b .` key binding.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] Pressing `C-b .` will prompt for a new index for the current window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p01] If a window already exists at the given index, an error will be shown.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If there are gaps in the window list, the indexes can be renumbered with the `-r` flag to `move-window`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Panes may be resized in small steps with `C-b C-Left`, `C-b C-Right`, `C-b C-Up` and `C-b C-Down` and in larger steps with `C-b M-Left`, `C-b M-Right`, `C-b M-Up` and `C-b M-Down`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A single pane may be temporarily made to take up the whole window with `C-b z`, hiding any other panes.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Pressing `C-b z` again puts the pane and window layout back to how it was.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A window where a pane has been zoomed is marked with a `Z` in the status line.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Commands that change the size or position of panes in a window automatically unzoom the window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The panes in a window may be automatically arranged into one of several named layouts, these may be rotated between with the `C-b Space` key binding or chosen directly with `C-b M-1`, `C-b M-2` and so on.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A piece of copied text is called a paste buffer.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Text is copied using copy mode, entered with `C-b [`, and the most recently copied text is pasted into the active pane with `C-b ]`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Paste buffers can be given names but by default they are assigned a name by tmux, such as `buffer0` or `buffer1`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Buffers like this are called automatic buffers and at most 50 are kept - once there are 50 buffers, the oldest is removed when another is added.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If a buffer is given a name, it is called a named buffer; named buffers are not deleted no matter how many there are.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] It is possible to configure tmux to send any copied text to the system clipboard: this document explains the different ways to configure this.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Copy mode freezes any output in a pane and allows text to be copied.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] View mode (described earlier) is a read-only form of copy mode.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Like the command prompt, copy mode uses keys similar to *emacs(1)*; however, if the `VISUAL` or `EDITOR` environment variables are set to something containing `vi`, then *vi(1)*-style keys are used instead.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A full list of keys for both *vi(1)* and *emacs(1)* is available in the manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Once some text is copied, the most recent may be pasted with `C-b ]` or an older buffer pasted by using buffer mode, entered with `C-b =`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Buffer mode is similar to client mode and tree mode and offers a list of buffers together with a preview of their contents.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A buffer may be renamed using the `set-buffer` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The `-b` flag gives the existing buffer name and `-n` the new name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `set-buffer` can also be used to create buffers.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `set-buffer` or `load-buffer` without `-b` creates an automatic buffer.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `C-b f` prompts for some text and then enters tree mode with a filter to show only panes where that text appears in the visible content or title of the pane or in the window name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If panes are found, only those panes appear in the tree, and the text `filter: active` is shown above the preview.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If no panes are found, all panes are shown in the tree and the text `filter: no matches` appears above the preview.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] It can be used to change the active pane or window, to resize panes, to copy text, or to choose items from menus.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Support for the mouse is enabled with the `mouse` option; options and the configuration file are described in detail in the next section.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] When the tmux server is started, tmux runs a file called `.tmux.conf` in the user's home directory.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] This file contains a list of tmux commands which are executed in order.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] It is important to note that `.tmux.conf` is *only* run when the server is started, not when a new session is created.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Commands in a configuration file appear one per line.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Although tmux configuration files have some features similar to the shell, they are not shell scripts and cannot use shell constructs like `$()`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] tmux key bindings are changed using the `bind-key` and `unbind-key` commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Each key binding in tmux belongs to a named key table.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] All the key bindings or those for a single table can be listed with the `list-keys` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] By default, this shows the keys as a series of `bind-key` commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The `-T` flag gives the key table to show and the `-N` flag shows the key help, like the `C-b ?` key binding.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `bind-key` commands can be used to set a key binding, either interactively or most commonly from the configuration file.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Like `list-keys`, `bind-key` has a `-T` flag for the key table to use.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If `-T` is not given, the key is put in the `prefix` table; the `-n` flag is a shorthand for `-Troot` to use the `root` table.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The `-t` flag to `select-window` specifies the target window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] In this example, the `:` means the target is a window and `=` means the name must match `10` exactly.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Targets are documented further in the COMMANDS section of the manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The `unbind-key` command removes a key binding.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Like `bind-key` it has `-T` and `-n` flags for the key table.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] It is not necessary to remove a key binding before binding it again, `bind-key` will replace any existing key binding.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Copy mode key bindings are set in the `copy-mode` and `copy-mode-vi` key tables.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] A full list of copy mode commands is available in the manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Session and window options have both a global set of options and a set for each session or window.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If the option is not present in the session or window set, the global option is used.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Pane options are similar except the window options are also checked.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] When configuring tmux, it is most common to set server options and global session or window options.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Options are displayed using the `show-options` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] An individual option value may be shown by giving its name to `show-option`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] When an option name is given, it is not necessary to give `-s` or `-w` because tmux can work it out from the option name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Options are set or unset using the `set-option` command.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Like `show-option`, it is not necessary to give `-s` or `-w` because tmux can work out it out from the option name.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `-g` is necessary to set global session or window options; for server options it does nothing.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Formats provide a powerful syntax to configure how text appears, based on various attributes of the tmux server, a session, window or pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Formats are enclosed in `#{}` in string options or as a single uppercase letter like `#F`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Formats are described in this document and in the manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Some options may contain embedded shell commands.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] This is limited to the status line options such as `status-left`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Embedded shell commands are enclosed in `#()`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Note that it is not usually necessary to use an embedded command for the date and time since tmux will expand the date formats like `%H` and `%S` itself in the status line options.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If a command like *date(1)* is used, any `%`s must be doubled as `%%`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] tmux allows the colour and attribute of text to be configured with a simple syntax, this is known as the style.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The remaining style terms are described in the manual page.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Embedded styles are included inside another option in between `#[` and `]`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Each changes the style of following text until the next embedded style or the end of the text.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] This section shows examples of some common configuration changes for `.tmux.conf`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The prefix key is set by the `prefix` option.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] The `C-b` key is also bound to the `send-prefix` command in the prefix key table so pressing `C-b` twice sends it through to the active pane.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] There are many options for customizing the status line.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] tmux supports key bindings based on *vi(1)* for copy mode and the command prompt.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] `status-keys` sets the key bindings for the command prompt.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] If either of the `VISUAL` or `EDITOR` environment variables are set to something containing `vi` (such as `vi`, `vim`, `nvi`) when the tmux server is first started, both of these options are set to `vi`.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] When dragging the mouse to copy text, tmux copies and exits copy mode when the mouse button is released.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] Alternative behaviours are configured by changing the `MouseDragEnd1Pane` key binding.
[src:tmux/getting-started-p02] tmux has a large set of features and commands not mentioned in this document, many allowing powerful scripting.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Released under the terms of version 3 or later of the GNU General Public License, GNU Screen is free software.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] GNU Screen can be thought of as a text version of graphical window managers, or as a way of putting virtual terminals into any login session.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] It is a wrapper that allows multiple text programs to run at the same time, and provides features that allow the user to use the programs within a single interface productively.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] This enables the following features: persistence, multiple windows, and session sharing.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Screen is often used when a network connection to the terminal is unreliable, as a dropped network connection typically terminates all programs the user was running (child processes of the login session), due to the session ending and sending a "hangup" signal (SIGHUP) to all the child processes.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Running the applications under screen means that the session does not terminate – only the now-defunct terminal gets detached – so applications don't even know the terminal has detached, and allows the user to reattach the session later and continue working from where they left off.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Screen was originally designed by Oliver Laumann and Carsten Bormann at Technische Universität Berlin and published in 1987.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Design criteria included VT100 emulation (including ANSI X3.64 (ISO 6429) and ISO 2022) and reasonable performance for heavy daily use when character-based terminals were still common.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Later, the at-the-time novel feature of disconnection/reattachment was added.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Around 1990, Laumann handed over maintenance of the code to Jürgen Weigert and Michael Schroeder at the University of Erlangen–Nuremberg, who later moved the project to the GNU Project and added features such as scrollback, split-screen, copy-and-paste, and screen sharing.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] By 2014, development had slowed to a crawl.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Wanting to change this, Amadeusz Sławiński volunteered to help.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] In response, Laumann granted him maintainership.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Sławiński proceeded to put out the first new Screen release in half a decade.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Because there were some unofficial "Screen 4.1" releases floating around the Internet, he called this new release "Screen 4.2.0".
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] In May 2015, on openSUSE Conference, Jürgen Weigert invited Alexander Naumov to help to develop and maintain GNU screen.
[src:tmux/gnu-screen] Two months later with Alex's help *GNU screen 4.3.0* was released.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] It is useful for dealing with multiple programs from a command line interface, and for separating programs from the session of the Unix shell that started the program, particularly so a remote process continues running even when the user is disconnected.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] A terminal multiplexer can be thought of as a text version of graphical window managers, or as a way of attaching virtual terminals to any login session.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] , many terminal multiplexers allow the user to start applications from one computer, and then reconnect from a different computer and continue using the same application without having to restart it.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] This makes accessing the same session between different locations like work and home simple.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] These multiplexers generally provide terminal-agnostic functionality so that users can disconnect and reconnect using different terminal types, allowing applications to continue running without being aware of the change in terminals.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] Concretely, the multiplexer starts a session (with associated processes), and then either does not attach a terminal to it, or attaches a terminal but can subsequently detach it (for example if the network connection is dropped).
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] ) and are not terminated, so they continue running, and one can subsequently (re)attach a terminal to the session and continue interacting, or simply leave the session unattached.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] Multiple terminal sessions can be created, each of which usually runs a single application.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] The windows are numbered, and the user can use the keyboard to switch between them.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] terminal emulators provide tabs or otherwise similar functionality to this.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] Each window has its own scroll-back buffer, so that output is captured even when the window isn't actively displayed, and that history can be saved even when migrating to another computer.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] While some text applications have this functionality built in, a terminal multiplexer allows any application to be split-screened alongside any number of other applications.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] Terminal multiplexers allow multiple computers to connect to the same session at once, enabling collaboration between multiple users.
[src:tmux/terminal-multiplexer] The same computer can also be used to make multiple simultaneous connections, providing alternative functionality to screen-splitting, particularly for computers with multiple monitors.
[src:tmux/tmux-tmux] It lets you switch easily between several programs in one terminal, detach them (they keep running in the background) and reattach them to a different terminal.
[src:tmux/tmux-tmux] Notes on tmux development and ideas for contributions are here.
[src:tmux/tmux-tmux] tmux merchandise 👕 is available from Commit Goods - purchases help support the tmux project.
[src:tmux/tmux-tmux] Or you can donate to tmux through GitHub.
[src:tmux/tmux] tmux includes most features of GNU Screen.
[src:tmux/tmux] tmux lacks built-in serial port and telnet support.
[src:tmux/tmux] It uses different command keys from the ones used by screen, so it is not a drop-in replacement for screen, but it can be configured to use compatible keybindings.
[src:tmux/tmux] tmux is included in the OpenBSD base system, and is available as a package for many other Unix-like operating systems.
